                <h3>Nutrition Monitoring (Football Training and Matches)</h3>
                <p>
                	For optimal performance in football you will need a lot of energy
                	for long lenghts of time, so it's essential that you have a well structured 
                	nutrition programme not only to provide energy for a training session, but to 
                	also provide fuel for recuperation for the next days exercise.
                </p>
                <p><a href="nutrition.jsp"><b>Back to Nutrition Page</b></a>
                <p><b>Football Training Nutrition</b></p>
                <ul>
                    <li><b>Breakfast:</b>
                    	<br>
                    	<ul>
	                    	<li>
	                    	Large bowl of porridge oats made with jumbo oats, 
	                    	+ 200ml of skimmed milk,
	                    	+ water with a tea spoon of suger and raisens if desired,
	                    	<br>
	                    	<br>	
	                    	or
	                    	<br>
	                    	<br>
	                    	</li>
	                    	
	                    	<li>
	                    	75g of unsweetened muesli + 250ml of skimmed milk,
	                    	250ml of fresh fruit juice,
	                    	Tea/Coffee
	                    	</li>
                    	</ul>
                    	<br>			
                    </li>
                    
                    <li><b>45 minutes pre-football training:</b>
                    	<ul>
                    		<li>2-3 oatcakes with low fat soft cheese</li>
                    		<li>Item of fruit</li>
                    		<li>Drink</li>
                    	</ul>
                    	<br>
                    </li>
                    <li><b>Football Training:</b>
                    	<ul>
                    		<li>90 minutes sip water or isotonic drink throughout</li>
                    	</ul>
                    	<br>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                    <b>Immediately post training:</b>
                    	<ul>
                    		<li>25g whey protein powder + 25g dextrose in water</li>
                    	</ul>
                    	<br>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                    <b>Lunch:</b>
                    	<ul>
                    		<li>Sandwich made with granary bread + olive oil basel spread with lean ham/chicken
                    		<br>
                    		<br>
                    		or
                    		<br>
                    		<br>
                    		</li>
                    		<li>large mackerel fillet</li>
                    		<li>100g mixed nuts and seeds</li>
                    		<li>Mixed salad</li>
                    		<li>Low fat,low sugar yoghurt</li>
                    		<li>Drink</li>
                    	</ul>
                    	<br>
                    </li>
                    <li><b>Gym Training:</b>
                    	<ul>
                    		<li>Drink Plenty of water before, after, and in between your exercises</li>
                    	</ul>
                    	<br>
                    </li>
                    <li><b>Immediately post workout:</b>
                    	<ul>
                    		<li>25g whey protein powder + 25g dextrose in water</li>
                    	</ul>
                    	<br>
                    </li>
                    <li><b>45 minutes later:</b>
                    	<ul>
                    		<li>2-3 oatcakes with low fat spft cheese</li>
                    		<li>100g mixed nuts and seeds</li>
                    		<li>Drink</li>
                    	</ul>
                    	<br>
                    </li>
                    <li><b>Evening Meal:</b>
                    	<ul>
                    		<li>
                    			Lean fillet steak or chicken breast or fish or herbs to taste<br>
                    			Boiled new potatoes or basmati or dry roasted sweet potatoes<br>
                    			Loads of mixed vegetables<br>
                    			Low fat, no added suger yoghurt<br>
                    			Drink
                    		</li>
                    	</ul>
                    	<br>
                    </li>
                    <li><b>1 hour pre-bed:</b>
                    	<ul>
                    		<li>
                    			100g cottege cheese / quark / low fat natural yoghurt<br>
                    			Banana<br>
                    			Small handful of mixed nuts and seeds<br>
                    			Drink
                    		</li>
                    	</ul>
                    	<br>
                    </li>
                </ul>
                <p>
	                The above plan provides sufficient levels of all nutrients and ssustained<br>
	                slow release of low glycaemic carbohydrates to help provide energy for long and intense training sessions.
